## Introduction

Next.js provides a static 404 page by default without having to add any additional files.
But you should customize the error pages if you would like to render them with your own page layout.

[//]:---excerpt---

## Environment
```sh
% node --version
v14.17.5
% yarn --version
1.22.11
% egrep '("react"|"next")' package.json
    "next": "~12.0.4",
    "react": "~17.0.2",
```

## How to customize the 404 error page
- create a `pages/404.jsx` (or .tsx) file.
```js
// pages/404.jsx
export default function Custom404() {
  return <h1>404 - Page Not Found</h1>;
}
```

<AdSense />

## How to customize the 500 error page
- create a `pages/500.jsx` (or .tsx) file.
```js
// pages/500.jsx
export default function Custom500() {
  return <h1>500 - Server-side error occurred</h1>;
}
```

## How to customize all error pages
- create a `pages/_error.jsx` (or .tsx) file.
- N.B.
  - pages/_error.js is only used in production. 
  - In development you’ll get an error with the call stack to know where the error originated from.
```js
// pages/_error.jsx
function Error({ statusCode }) {
  return (
    <p>
      {statusCode
        ? `An error ${statusCode} occurred on server`
        : 'An error occurred on client'}
    </p>
  );
}

Error.getInitialProps = ({ res, err }) => {
  const statusCode = res ? res.statusCode : err ? err.statusCode : 404;
  return { statusCode };
}
```

<AdSense />

## Conclusion

You can customize all the error pages with one file, `pages/_error.tsx`, as below.
It works on both CSR(Client-Side Rendering) and SSR(Server-Side Rendering).
```ts
// _error.tsx

import { NextPageContext } from "next";
import { PageLayout } from "../my-components";

interface Props {
  statusCode: number;
}

export default function Error({ statusCode }: Props) {
  return (
    <PageLayout>
      <h1>
        {/* CSR env: statusCode is 'undefined'
            SSR env: statusCode has an error code */}
        {!statusCode || statusCode === 404
          ? "404 - Page Not Found"
          : `An error ${statusCode} occurred on server`}
      </h1>
    </PageLayout>
  );
}

Error.getInitialProps = ({ res, err }: NextPageContext) => {
  const statusCode = res ? res.statusCode : err ? err.statusCode : 404;
  return { statusCode };
};
```

## Reference

- [Custom Error Page](https://nextjs.org/docs/advanced-features/custom-error-page#404-page)

## Introduction

```txt
`px` `em` `rem` `vw` `vh` `vmin` `vmax`
```

What is all of these?

They are a unit used in CSS. But why such many units are necessary?

Let's figure out one by one.

No time? Then go to [Conclusion](#conclusion)

[//]:---excerpt---

## What is PX(PiXel)?

- `px` is an absolute and fixed-size unit.
- The physical size of 1`px` is dependent on a screen resolution.

## What is EM(M)?

- `em` is a relative unit to ***a parent element***.
- 1`em` is the 'font-size' defined in the parent element.
- For example, 1`em` has a different pixel value by it's parent element.

```css
div {
  font-size: 16px;
}
span {
  font-size: 8px;
}
p {
  font-size: 1em;
}
```

```html
<div> <p> 1em is 16px here </p> </div>
<span> <p> 1em is 8px here </p> </span>
```

## When to use EM?

- It's good for responsive components.

<AdSense />

## What is REM(Root EM)?

- `rem` is a relative unit to ***a root element***.
- 1`rem` is the pixel size defined in the root element.
- For example, if you set the 'font-size' to 10`px` as follows, 1`rem` is translated into 10`px` by the browser.

```css
html {
  font-size: 16px;
}
p {
  font-size: 1rem; /* <== translated into 10px */
}
```

## When to use REM?

- It's good for responsive web pages.
- You can set the 'font-size' by divices using the 'media' query as follows:

```css
html {
  /* Extra small devices (phones, 600px and down) */
  @media only screen and (max-width: 600px) {
    font-size: 10px;
  }
  /* Small devices (portrait tablets and large phones, 600px and up) */
  @media only screen and (min-width: 600px) {
    font-size: 12px;
  }

  /* Medium devices (landscape tablets, 768px and up) */
  @media only screen and (min-width: 768px) {
    font-size: 18px;
  }

  /* Large devices (laptops/desktops, 992px and up) */
  @media only screen and (min-width: 992px) {
    font-size: 26px;
  }

  /* Extra large devices (large laptops and desktops, 1200px and up) */
  @media only screen and (min-width: 1200px) {
    font-size: 34px;
  }
}

p {
  font-size: 1rem;
}
```

## What is `vh`, `vw`, `vmin` and `vmax`?

- `v*` are a relative unit to ***a viewport***
- 1`vw` is 1 percentage of a viewport width
- 1`vh` is 1 percentage of a viewport height
- 1`vmin` is min(1`vh`, 1`vw`)
- 1`vmax` is max(1`vh`, 1`vw`)
- In portrait orientation,
  - 1`vmin` is 1`vw`
  - 1`vmax` is 1`vh`
- In landscape orientation,
  - 1`vmin` is 1`vh`
  - 1`vmax` is 1`vw`

<AdSense />

## Conclusion

| Unit | Dependency         | Unit size in pixel               |
|------|--------------------|----------------------------------|
| em   | parent element     |  1em = parent element pixel size |
| rem  | root element       | 1rem = root element pixel size   |
| vw   | viewport width     | 1vw = 1% of viewport width       |
| vh   | viewport height    | 1vh = 1% of viewport height      |
| vmin | device orientation | 1vmin = min(1vh, 1vw)            |
| vmax | device orientation | 1vmax = max(1vh, 1vw)            |

<br/>

- For example,
- viewport width: 100px, viewport height: 200px
- css is as follows:

<JSCodeTabs
  html={`<p class="em-ele"> 10px (parent is root) </p>
<p class="rem-ele"> 10px ()</p>
<div>
  <p class="em-ele"> 20px (parent is div) </p>
  <p class="rem-ele"> 10px (root is the one)</p>
<div>
<p class="vh-ele"> 2px (= 200px * 1%) </p>
<p class="vw-ele"> 1px (= 100px * 1%) </p>
<p class="vmin-ele"> 1px (= min(2px, 1px)) </p>
<p class="vmax-ele"> 2px (= max(2px, 1px)) </p>`}
  css={`html {
  font-size: 10px;
}
div {
  font-size: 20px;
}
.em-ele {
  font-size: 1em;
}
.rem-ele {
  font-size: 1rem;
}
.vh-ele {
  font-size: 1vh;
}
.vw-ele {
  font-size: 1vw;
}
.vmin-ele {
  font-size: 1vmin;
}
.vmax-ele {
  font-size: 1vmax;
}`}
  useTable={true}
/>

